ated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]]  <small>Shared with [[Marvin Hamlisch]], [[Robert John Lange]] and [[Bryan Adams]] for the song \"[[I Finally Found Someone]]\"</small>\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Meet the Fockers]]''\n|Rozalin \"Roz\" Focker\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Little Fockers]]''\n|Rozalin \"Roz\" Focker\n| Nominated\u2014[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[The Guilt Trip (film)|The Guilt Trip]]''\n| Joyce Brewster\n| Nominated\u2014[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]]\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Wikipedia books|Barbra Streisand}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Andersen|first=Christopher|title=Barbra: The Way She Is|location=|publisher=Harper-Collins|year=2006|isbn=0-06-056256-0}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Edwards|first=Anne|title=Streisand: A Biography|publisher=Little, Brown|year=1997|isbn=978-0-316-21138-3}}\n*Gabler, Neal. (2016). ''Barbra Streisand: Redefining Beauty, Femininity, and Power'', Yale University Press {{ISBN|978-0300210910}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Pohly|first=Linda|title=The Barbra Streisand Companion: A Guide to Her Vocal Style and Repertoire|location=|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=2000|isbn=0-313-30414-9|url=https://archive.org/details/barbrastreisandc00lind}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Riese|first=Randall|title=Her Name Is Barbra: An Intimate Portrait of the Real Barbra Streisand|publisher=Birch Lane Press|year=1993|isbn=1-55972-203-7|url=https://archive.org/details/hernameisbarbrai00ries_0}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Santopietro|first=Tom|title=The Importance of Being Barbra: The Brilliant, Tumultuous Career of Barbra Streisand|publisher=Thomas Dunne|year=2006|isbn=978-0-312-34879-3|url=https://archive.org/details/importanceofbein00sant}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Schapiro|first=Steve|last2=Schiller|first2=Lawrence|year=2016|title=Barbra Streisand|publisher=Taschen|isbn=9783836563239}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Spada|first=James|title=Streisand: Her Life|location=|publisher=Crown Publishers, Inc|year=1995|isbn=0-517-59753-5}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Barbra Streisand}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.barbrastreisand.com/}}\n* {{Britannica|568756}}\n* {{allmovie name|112652}}\n* {{allmusic|artist/barbra-streisand-mn0000855531}}\n* {{IMDb name|659}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=185903|name=Barbra Streisand}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|29830|Barbra Streisand}}\n\n{{Barbra Streisand}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Barbra Streisand\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestActress 1961\u20131980}}\n{{AcademyAwardBestOriginalSong 1971\u20131980}}\n{{AFI Life Achievement Award}}\n{{Cecil B. DeMille Award 1976\u20132000}}\n{{David di Donatello for Best Foreign Actress}}\n{{EmmyAward VarietyPerformance}}\n{{Lincoln Center Gala Tribute}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestActressMotionPictureMusicalComedy 1961\u20131980}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Director 1966\u20131990}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song}}\n{{Grammy Award for Album of the Year 1960s}}\n{{Grammy Award for Song of the Year 1970s}}\n{{Grammy Legend Award}}\n{{Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award}}\n{{Kennedy Center Honorees 2000s}}\n{{MusiCares Person of the Year}}\n{{National Medal of Arts recipients 2000s}}\n{{People's Choice Award for Favorite Movie Actress}}\n{{Special Tony Award}}\n}}\n{{Billboard Year-End number one singles 1960\u20131979}}\n{{UK best-selling albums (by year) 1970\u20131989}}\n\n{{EGOT winners}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Streisand, Barbra}}\n[[Category:Barbra Streisand| ]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American female pop singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:French-language singers of the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Torch singers]]\n[[Category:Traditional pop music singers]]\n<!--awards + honors-->\n[[Category:Best Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Actress Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n[[Category:Best Director Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Best Original Song Academy Award-winning songwriters]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Cecil B. DeMille Award Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello winners]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Legend Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award winners]]\n[[Category:Kennedy Center honorees]]\n[[Category:Nixon's Enemies List]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:United States National Medal of Arts recipients]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Jewish singers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n<!--from-->\n[[Category:Erasmus Hall High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Liberalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Flatbush, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from California]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Singers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Ballad musicians]]\n[[Category:AFI Life Achievement Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas shows]]\n", "name_user": "Shantavira", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision appearances, marriage and first albums:wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbra_Streisand"}
{"title_page": "Iceboat", "text_new": "[[File:Dn nasva 0820.jpg|300px|thumb|An iceboat at the 2011 DN European Championships  in [[Nasva, Saare County|Nasva]], [[Estonia]]]]\n[[File:IJszeilen op de Gouwzee Weeknummer 38-52 - Open Beelden - 50860.ogv|thumb|right|Ice sailing in the Netherlands in 1938.]]\nAn '''iceboat''' (occasionally spelled '''ice boat''' or traditionally called an '''ice yacht''') is a recreational or competition sailing craft supported on metal runners for traveling over ice. One of the runners is steerable. Originally, such craft were boats with a support structure, riding on the runners and steered with a rear blade, as with a conventional rudder. As iceboats evolved, the structure became a frame with a seat or cockpit for the iceboat sailor, resting on runners. Steering was shifted to the front. \n\nBecause of their low resistance to forward motion over ice, iceboats are capable of speeds exceeding {{Convert|60|mph|km/h|abbr=}}. Because of their speed, iceboats are used both for recreation and for racing. Racing craft typically carry one person.\n\nA related activity, [[land sailing]], employs sailing craft similar to iceboats, but riding on wheels instead of runners.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ice boat (Quebec).jpg|thumb|Ice boat on [[Saint Lawrence River]], [[Quebec City]], ca 1858-1860]]\n[[File:Ice yachters on Hudson River near Barrytown, NY.jpg|thumb|right|Classic iceboats on the [[Hudson River]] at [[Barrytown, New York|Barrytown, NY]]|alt=Several boats with their sails at various stages of dismantling surrounding a large vehicle with a wooded promontory behind them. In the far right upper background a portion of a bridge is visible]]\nThe history of iceboating began in Europe in areas where smooth ice was found in the bays of the Baltic Sea and the canals of the Netherlands. Initially boats were used for commerce, but soon evolved into pleasure craft\u2014\"ice yachts\". Ice sailing came to North America, where the sailing craft evolved into recreational and racing versions.\n\n=== Venues ===\nIceboating began in the 17th century as a documented means of transport on the frozen Gulf of Riga and the canals of the Netherlands into the 18th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/sports/iceboating|title=Iceboating {{!}} sport|last=Editors|first=|date=February 17, 2020|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Ice boats carried cargo on Dutch canals during the 17th century.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Spectre|first=Peter H.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/173009383|title=A mariner's book of days, 2007|date=2006|publisher=Sheridan House|year=|isbn=1-57409-226-X|location=Dobbs Ferry, NY|pages=|oclc=173009383}}</ref> \n\nThe first iceboats were introduced on New York State's Hudson River in the United States in 1790, where the practice flourished as a sport. The first recorded boat, built in 1790 by Oliver Booth of Poughkeepsie, was a square box atop three runners, the two forward runners being nailed to the box and the third acted as a rudder operated by a tiller. This type of craft was accessible to sportsmen of modest means.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://hvmag.com/things-to-do/explore-the-history-of-ice-yachting-in-the-hudson-valley/|title=Explore the History of Ice Yachting in the Hudson Valley|last=Levine|first=David|date=|website=www.hvmag.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-19th century, two \"ice yachting\" clubs had formed, the Poughkeepsie Ice Yacht Club (1865) and the Hudson River Ice Yacht Club (1870), where wealthy boat owners sailed large iceboats with up to seven crew members. Boats were as long as {{Convert|69|ft|m|abbr=}} and sailed as fast as {{Convert|107|mi/h|km/h|abbr=}}, a record exceeding any other conveyance in 1885, set by the ''[[Icicle (yacht)|Icicle]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first American Challenge Pennant occurred in 1881 on the Hudson river with five ice-yacht clubs competing. Races were sailed five times around a triangular course with one-mile legs, two of which were to windward. Iceboats were divided into four classes with sail areas ranging from less than 300 square feet to over 600 square feet.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1911|isbn=|editor-last=Chisholm|editor-first=Hugh|edition=11|volume=14|location=|pages=241\u2013242|chapter=Ice-Yachting}}</ref>\n\nBy the beginning of the 20th century, iceboating had spread to Minnesota ([[Lake Minnetonka]] and [[White Bear Lake, Minnesota|White Bear Lake]]), Wisconsin ([[Lake Winnebago]] and [[Lake Pepin]]) and venues in Maine and Vermont. In Canada, there were venues on [[Lake Ontario]] (Kingston) and the [[Saint Lawrence River]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nA European ice sailing club formed first in Sweden (1901), followed by the European Ice Yachting Union, which formed in 1928 with member states Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia, Sweden, Austria, and Germany.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Evolution of design ===\n[[File:Vinckboons Landscape with skaters.jpg|thumb|Dutch Iceboats, 17th century]]\n17th-century Dutch ice yachts consisted of flat-bottomed sailboats atop a cross-wise plank, resting on outboard metal runners, which carried the bulk of the weight of the craft. At the stern was a steering runner, attached to a rudder-like structure. to which are affixed four steel runners, one each at bow, stern and each end of the planking. These boats used conventional gaff mainsails and jibs, attached to the mast by travellers. A tiller or wheel stern controls the steering runner.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the 19th century iceboats evolved into a box, riding on cross-pieces, supported by runners. These \"stern-steerer\" iceboats were generally rigged as [[sloop]]s, with a [[jib]] sail forward of the mast, although the [[catboat]] style with a single sail was also used.<ref name=\":03\" /> In 1879 the archetypical Hudson River iceboat began to emerge. The ''Robert Scott'', designed and built by H. Relyea, had a single backbone and wire guy-ropes. The mast on subsequent boats were stepped further forward than in the past with shortened jibs were shortened and the center of effort and resistance brought into balance, aligning both with the main runners.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danielfisher/2014/03/07/as-the-hudson-river-freezes-over-classic-ice-yachts-emerge/|title=As The Hudson River Freezes, Classic Ice Yachts Emerge|last=Fisher|first=Daniel|date=March 7, 2014|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The shallow cockpit box became elliptical.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the early 1900s some smaller iceboats, called ''scooters'', were designed to traverse both ice and water with a shallow, oval {{Convert|15*5|ft|m|abbr=}} hull on fixed runners. These sailing craft were steered by manipulating the sails, there being no rudder.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe traditional stern-steerer boats were largely replaced by front steering boats in the 1930s, following the development of this style by Walter Beauvois of [[Williams Bay, Wisconsin]] in a boat named the ''Beau Skeeter''.<ref name=\":4\" /> This boat led to the \"Skeeter\" class, and the ''Skeeter Ice Boat Club'' formed on [[Geneva Lake]], Wisconsin. The Skeeter class adopted the logo of a mosquito on their sail, and has evolved into an [[Aerodynamics|aerodynamically clean]] machine. The Skeeter class is limited to just {{convert|75|sqft|m2}} of sail.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Andrews|first=Candice Gaukel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OlmGjEU7qU4C&pg=PA152&dq=%22skeeter+iceboat%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjWs8eQoOnoAhVPlnIEHQMiCZIQ6AEwAHoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=skeeter&f=false|title=Great Wisconsin Winter Weekends|date=2006|publisher=Big Earth Publishing|year=|isbn=978-1-931599-71-9|location=|pages=152|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1937, ''[[The Detroit News]]'' sponsored a new home-buildable ice boat design, which became the [[International DN]]. In 1968 Dick Slates of [[Pewaukee, Wisconsin]] designed and built the ''Nite'' with two wooden prototypes. The design was refined and fiberglass production began in 1970.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Speed==\n[[File:Ice boat apparent wind on different points of sail.jpg|thumb|Diagram of apparent wind (V<sub>A</sub>) on an iceboat on different points of sail ]]\nIceboats designs dating from the mid 20th century onwards typically consist of a triangular or cross-shaped frame, supported by three skate blades called \"runners\", with the steering runner in front. Runners are made of iron or steel and sharpened to a fine edge, most often cut to an angled edge of 90 degrees, which holds onto the ice, preventing slippage sideways from the lateral force of the wind developed by the sails, as they develop [[Forces on sails|propulsive lift]]. Given their low forward resistance, iceboats can sail up to five times the speed of the true wind.<ref name=Boat_Speed>{{Citation\n | first = Bob\n | last = Dill\n | contribution = Sailing Yacht Design for Maximum Speed\n | contribution-url = http://static1.1.sqspcdn.com/static/f/572109/24503675/1394724903587/Sailing+Yacht+Design+for+Maximum+Speed.pdf?token=5pzNaaWIFu%2F7e3pN5RiQ2e6MmmM%3D\n | title = The 16th Chesapeake Sailing Yacht Symposium\n | date = March 2003\n | pages =\n | place = Anapolis\n | publisher = SNAME\n | url = http://www.sname.org/chesapeakesailingyachtsymposiumcsys/pastpapers/16thcsys }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Editors|title=Commonly Asked Questions|url=http://iceboat.org/faqiceboat.html|publisher=Four Lakes Ice Yacht Club|accessdate=2010-08-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110309200937/http://www.iceboat.org/faqiceboat.html|archive-date=2011-03-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> Because the velocity of the iceboat (V<sub>B</sub>) is so much greater than the true wind velocity (V<sub>T</sub>), the apparent wind (V<sub>A</sub>) is only a few degrees from the direction of travel on most [[Point of sail|points of sail]] and the sail is close-hauled in each. V<sub>A</sub> is generated by the combination of iceboat velocity (V<sub>B</sub>) and true wind velocity (V<sub>T</sub>).<ref>See page 204 of {{cite book\n |last = Bethwaite\n |first = Frank\n |title = High Performance Sailing\n |publisher = Adlard Coles Nautical\n |year = 2007\n |isbn = 978-0-7136-6704-2}}</ref>\n\n=== Attainable speeds ===\nDifferent classes of iceboat can achieve speeds, as follow. \n\n* International DN: {{Convert|55-68|mph|km/h|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Boat_Speed\">{{Citation\n | first = Bob\n | last = Dill\n | contribution = Sailing Yacht Design for Maximum Speed\n | contribution-url = http://static1.1.sqspcdn.com/static/f/572109/24503675/1394724903587/Sailing+Yacht+Design+for+Maximum+Speed.pdf?token=5pzNaaWIFu%2F7e3pN5RiQ2e6MmmM%3D\n | title = The 16th Chesapeake Sailing Yacht Symposium\n | date = March 2003\n | pages =\n | place = Anapolis\n | publisher = SNAME\n | url = http://www.sname.org/chesapeakesailingyachtsymposiumcsys/pastpapers/16thcsys }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dill|first=Bob|date=February 2004|title=Putting Numbers on Iceboat Performance|url=https://www.nalsa.org/Articles/Cetus/Iceboat%20Sailing%20Performance-Cetus.pdf|journal=International DN Ice Yacht Racing Association Newsletter|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n* Classic iceboats and Skeeters: {{Convert|100-150|mph|km/h|abbr=}}. Record: ''Das Boot'', {{Convert|155.9|mph|km/h|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":4\" /> Record: classic iceboat, ''Debutaunte'', {{Convert|143|mph|km/h|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Boat_Speed\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Smith|first=Doug|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=dn+ice+boat+speed+record&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-luSX8-roAhU8knIEHW7eA2AQ6AEwA3oECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=dn%20ice%20boat%20speed%20record&f=false|title=Sailing on slivers of steel|date=January-February 2004|work=Scouting|publisher=Boy Scouts of America, Inc.|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=18-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Race courses ===\nBecause of the high boat speeds, iceboat race courses are established around fixed marks which are to be rounded in a one-way route, enhancing boat-to-boat traffic safety. The courses are a straight line [[upwind]] and [[downwind]], which necessitates [[Tacking (sailing)|tacking]] upwind and [[Jibe|jibing]] downwind.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Classes==\n[[File:Regaty bojerowe w klasie DN na Jeziorze Du\u017cym w \u017bninie.jpg|thumb|DN class iceboats at the start of a race in [[Znin]], [[Poland]]]]\n[[File:JWC-JEC 2019 IceOptimists.jpg|thumb|IceOptimists]]\n[[File:SIK-N157 14.jpg|thumb|Monotype XV]]\n\n=== International DN ===\nThe [[International DN]] class is the most popular class in both North America and Europe. It is a one-person wood boat twelve feet long with a cross-plank eight feet long that carries a mast {{convert|16|ft|m}} high. Modern competitive DNs use flexible masts commonly made of composite materials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227121944/https://ice.idniyra.org/|title=IDNIYRA {{!}} International DN Ice Yacht Racing Association|date=2017-12-27|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The DN 60 derives its name from the 1937 request of ''The Detroit News'' for a high-performance, inexpensive, home-built iceboat design. Modern DNs share many one-design features with the original boat, including the basic aerodynamic fuselage design, runner configurations and {{convert|60|sqft|m2}} of high-performance sail.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Staff|first=|date=January 1982|title=Endless winter, the iceboater's dream|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mgMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA59&dq=skeeter+ice+boat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjB0fvbnOnoAhWohHIEHQrjBWUQ6AEwAnoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=skeeter%20ice%20boat&f=false|journal=Changing Times-The Kiplinger Magazine|volume=36|issue=1|pages=58-9|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== IceOptimist ===\nThe IceOptimist is a youth iceboat class that uses the sails and the rig of the [[Optimist (dinghy)|International Optimist dinghy]]. The first design was built in [[Estonia]] in 1978, with scaled-down elements of a [[International DN|DN]]. In [[2002]], the class was registered under the guardianship of IDNIYRA Europe with the permission of IODA. World and European Championships are sailed each winter with a fleet of approximately 40 racers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idniyra.eu/juniors/|title=ICE OPTI and DN JUNIOR \u2013 IDNIYRA \u2013 Europe|website=idniyra.eu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Monotype XV ===\nThe Monotype XV is a class of iceboat based on a 1932 design by Estonian, Erik von Holst. It may be single or double-handed. The [[One-Design|one-design]] class is built according to close specifications, little changed since the 1930s. It is the largest one-design iceboat class in Europe and the only double-handed iceboat class for which there are international championships. The {{Convert|205|kg|lb|abbr=|adj=on}} is {{Convert|7.5*4.2|m|ft|abbr=}} in length and width with a {{Convert|7.2|m|ft|abbr=|adj=on}} high mast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iceboat.org/2019/03/04/monotype-xv-european-championship/|title=Monotype XV European Championship|last=Whitehorse|first=Deb|date=2019-03-04|website=iceboat.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Skeeter ===\nThe Skeeter class is divided into sub-classes (A, B and C) all of which are limited to {{convert|75|sqft|m2}} of sail area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iceboat.org/regattas/internationalskeeterassociation/|title=International Skeeter Association|website=iceboat.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> ''A-class'' boats may be single or two-place tandem with a mast that does not exceed {{Convert|28.5|ft|m|abbr=}}. They may incorporate carbon fiber construction.<ref name=\":3\" /> ''B-class'' boats have seats for two (side by side). ''C-class'' skeeters may be single or two-place tandem with a mast that does not exceed {{Convert|20.25|ft|m|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://139655-585885-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/ISARules.pdf|title=General rules and regulations of the International Skeeter Association|last=Class committee|first=|date=October 16, 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Sail boat]]\n* [[Sailing]]\n* [[Land sailing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PE8mCZOmrEo Video overview of DN iceboating]\n* {{Commons category-inline|Iceboats}}\n\n{{Application of wind energy}}\n{{Ice}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ice Boat}}\n[[Category:Ice yachting]]\n[[Category:Sailboat types]]\n[[Category:Racing vehicles]]\n[[Category:Human-powered watercraft]]\n\n[[de:Eissegeln]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Dn nasva 0820.jpg|300px|thumb|An iceboat at the 2011 DN European Championships  in [[Nasva, Saare County|Nasva]], [[Estonia]]]]\n[[File:IJszeilen op de Gouwzee Weeknummer 38-52 - Open Beelden - 50860.ogv|thumb|right|Ice sailing in the Netherlands in 1938.]]\nAn '''iceboat''' (occasionally spelled '''ice boat''' or traditionally called an '''ice yacht''') is a recreational or competition sailing craft supported on metal runners for traveling over ice. One of the runners is steerable. Originally, such craft were boats with a support structure, riding on the runners and steered with a rear blade, as with a conventional rudder. As iceboats evolved, the structure became a frame with a seat or cockpit for the iceboat sailor, resting on runners. Steering was shifted to the front. \n\nBecause of their low resistance to forward motion over ice, iceboats are capable of speeds exceeding {{Convert|60|mph|km/h|abbr=}}. Because of their speed, iceboats are used both for recreation and for racing. Racing craft typically carry one person.\n\nA related activity, [[land sailing]], employs sailing craft similar to iceboats, but riding on wheels instead of runners.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ice boat (Quebec).jpg|thumb|Ice boat on [[Saint Lawrence River]], [[Quebec City]], ca 1858-1860]]\n[[File:Ice yachters on Hudson River near Barrytown, NY.jpg|thumb|right|Classic iceboats on the [[Hudson River]] at [[Barrytown, New York|Barrytown, NY]]|alt=Several boats with their sails at various stages of dismantling surrounding a large vehicle with a wooded promontory behind them. In the far right upper background a portion of a bridge is visible]]\nThe history of iceboating began in Europe in areas where smooth ice was found in the bays of the Baltic Sea and the canals of the Netherlands. Initially boats were used for commerce, but soon evolved into pleasure craft\u2014\"ice yachts\". Ice sailing came to North America, where the sailing craft evolved into recreational and racing versions.\n\n=== Venues ===\nIceboating began in the 17th century as a documented means of transport on the frozen Gulf of Riga and the canals of the Netherlands into the 18th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/sports/iceboating|title=Iceboating {{!}} sport|last=Editors|first=|date=February 17, 2020|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Ice boats carried cargo on Dutch canals during the 17th century.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Spectre|first=Peter H.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/173009383|title=A mariner's book of days, 2007|date=2006|publisher=Sheridan House|year=|isbn=1-57409-226-X|location=Dobbs Ferry, NY|pages=|oclc=173009383}}</ref> \n\nThe first iceboats were introduced on New York State's Hudson River in the United States in 1790, where the practice flourished as a sport. The first recorded boat, built in 1790 by Oliver Booth of Poughkeepsie, was a square box atop three runners, the two forward runners being nailed to the box and the third acted as a rudder operated by a tiller. This type of craft was accessible to sportsmen of modest means.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://hvmag.com/things-to-do/explore-the-history-of-ice-yachting-in-the-hudson-valley/|title=Explore the History of Ice Yachting in the Hudson Valley|last=Levine|first=David|date=|website=www.hvmag.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-19th century, two \"ice yachting\" clubs had formed, the Poughkeepsie Ice Yacht Club (1865) and the Hudson River Ice Yacht Club (1870), where wealthy boat owners sailed large iceboats with up to seven crew members. Boats were as long as {{Convert|69|ft|m|abbr=}} and sailed as fast as {{Convert|107|mi/h|km/h|abbr=}}, a record exceeding any other conveyance in 1885, set by the ''[[Icicle (yacht)|Icicle]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first American Challenge Pennant occurred in 1881 on the Hudson river with five ice-yacht clubs competing. Races were sailed five times around a triangular course with one-mile legs, two of which were to windward. Iceboats were divided into four classes with sail areas ranging from less than 300 square feet to over 600 square feet.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1911|isbn=|editor-last=Chisholm|editor-first=Hugh|edition=11|volume=14|location=|pages=241\u2013242|chapter=Ice-Yachting}}</ref>\n\nBy the beginning of the 20th century, iceboating had spread to Minnesota ([[Lake Minnetonka]] and [[White Bear Lake, Minnesota|White Bear Lake]]), Wisconsin ([[Lake Winnebago]] and [[Lake Pepin]]) and venues in Maine and Vermont. In Canada, there were venues on [[Lake Ontario]] (Kingston) and the [[Saint Lawrence River]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nA European ice sailing club formed first in Sweden (1901), followed by the European Ice Yachting Union, which formed in 1928 with member states Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia, Sweden, Austria, and Germany.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Evolution of design ===\n[[File:Vinckboons Landscape with skaters.jpg|thumb|Dutch Iceboats, 17th century]]\n17th-century Dutch ice yachts consisted of flat-bottomed sailboats atop a cross-wise plank, resting on outboard metal runners, which carried the bulk of the weight of the craft. At the stern was a steering runner, attached to a rudder-like structure. to which are affixed four steel runners, one each at bow, stern and each end of the planking. These boats used conventional gaff mainsails and jibs, attached to the mast by travellers. A tiller or wheel stern controls the steering runner.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the 19th century iceboats evolved into a box, riding on cross-pieces, supported by runners. These \"stern-steerer\" iceboats were generally rigged as [[sloop]]s, with a [[jib]] sail forward of the mast, although the [[catboat]] style with a single sail was also used.<ref name=\":03\" /> In 1879 the archetypical Hudson River iceboat began to emerge. The ''Robert Scott'', designed and built by H. Relyea, had a single backbone and wire guy-ropes. The mast on subsequent boats were stepped further forward than in the past with shortened jibs were shortened and the center of effort and resistance brought into balance, aligning both with the main runners.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danielfisher/2014/03/07/as-the-hudson-river-freezes-over-classic-ice-yachts-emerge/|title=As The Hudson River Freezes, Classic Ice Yachts Emerge|last=Fisher|first=Daniel|date=March 7, 2014|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The shallow cockpit box became elliptical.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the early 1900s some smaller iceboats, called ''scooters'', were designed to traverse both ice and water with a shallow, oval {{Convert|15*5|ft|m|abbr=}} hull on fixed runners. These sailing craft were steered by manipulating the sails, there being no rudder.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe traditional stern-steerer boats were largely replaced by front steering boats in the 1930s, following the development of this style by Walter Beauvois of [[Williams Bay, Wisconsin]] in a boat named the ''Beau Skeeter''.<ref name=\":4\" /> This boat led to the \"Skeeter\" class, and the ''Skeeter Ice Boat Club'' formed on [[Geneva Lake]], Wisconsin. The Skeeter class adopted the logo of a mosquito on their sail, and has evolved into an [[Aerodynamics|aerodynamically clean]] machine. The Skeeter class is limited to just {{convert|75|sqft|m2}} of sail.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Andrews|first=Candice Gaukel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OlmGjEU7qU4C&pg=PA152&dq=%22skeeter+iceboat%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjWs8eQoOnoAhVPlnIEHQMiCZIQ6AEwAHoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=skeeter&f=false|title=Great Wisconsin Winter Weekends|date=2006|publisher=Big Earth Publishing|year=|isbn=978-1-931599-71-9|location=|pages=152|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1937, ''[[The Detroit News]]'' sponsored a new home-buildable ice boat design, which became the [[International DN]]. In 1968 Dick Slates of [[Pewaukee, Wisconsin]] designed and built the ''Nite'' with two wooden prototypes. The design was refined and fiberglass production began in 1970.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Speed==\n[[File:Ice boat apparent wind on different points of sail.jpg|thumb|Diagram of apparent wind (V<sub>A</sub>) on an iceboat on different points of sail ]]\nIceboats designs dating from the mid 20th century onwards typically consist of a triangular or cross-shaped frame, supported by three skate blades called \"runners\", with the steering runner in front. Runners are made of iron or steel and sharpened to a fine edge, most often cut to an angled edge of 90 degrees, which holds onto the ice, preventing slippage sideways from the lateral force of the wind developed by the sails, as they develop [[Forces on sails|propulsive lift]]. Given their low forward resistance, iceboats can sail up to ten times the speed of the true wind. Because the velocity of the iceboat (V<sub>B</sub>) is so much greater than the true wind velocity (V<sub>T</sub>), the apparent wind (V<sub>A</sub>) is only a few degrees from the direction of travel on most [[Point of sail|points of sail]] and the sail is close-hauled in each. V<sub>A</sub> is generated by the combination of iceboat velocity (V<sub>B</sub>) and true wind velocity (V<sub>T</sub>).<ref>See page 204 of {{cite book\n |last = Bethwaite\n |first = Frank\n |title = High Performance Sailing\n |publisher = Adlard Coles Nautical\n |year = 2007\n |isbn = 978-0-7136-6704-2}}</ref>\n\n=== Attainable speeds ===\nDifferent classes of iceboat can achieve speeds, as follow. \n\n* International DN: {{Convert|55-68|mph|km/h|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Boat_Speed\">{{Citation\n | first = Bob\n | last = Dill\n | contribution = Sailing Yacht Design for Maximum Speed\n | contribution-url = http://static1.1.sqspcdn.com/static/f/572109/24503675/1394724903587/Sailing+Yacht+Design+for+Maximum+Speed.pdf?token=5pzNaaWIFu%2F7e3pN5RiQ2e6MmmM%3D\n | title = The 16th Chesapeake Sailing Yacht Symposium\n | date = March 2003\n | pages =\n | place = Anapolis\n | publisher = SNAME\n | url = http://www.sname.org/chesapeakesailingyachtsymposiumcsys/pastpapers/16thcsys }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dill|first=Bob|date=February 2004|title=Putting Numbers on Iceboat Performance|url=https://www.nalsa.org/Articles/Cetus/Iceboat%20Sailing%20Performance-Cetus.pdf|journal=International DN Ice Yacht Racing Association Newsletter|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n* Classic iceboats and Skeeters: {{Convert|100-150|mph|km/h|abbr=}}. Record: ''Das Boot'', {{Convert|155.9|mph|km/h|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":4\" /> Record: classic iceboat, ''Debutaunte'', {{Convert|143|mph|km/h|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Boat_Speed\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Smith|first=Doug|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=dn+ice+boat+speed+record&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-luSX8-roAhU8knIEHW7eA2AQ6AEwA3oECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=dn%20ice%20boat%20speed%20record&f=false|title=Sailing on slivers of steel|date=January-February 2004|work=Scouting|publisher=Boy Scouts of America, Inc.|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=18-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Race courses ===\nBecause of the high boat speeds, iceboat race courses are established around fixed marks which are to be rounded in a one-way route, enhancing boat-to-boat traffic safety. The courses are a straight line [[upwind]] and [[downwind]], which necessitates [[Tacking (sailing)|tacking]] upwind and [[Jibe|jibing]] downwind.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Classes==\n[[File:Regaty bojerowe w klasie DN na Jeziorze Du\u017cym w \u017bninie.jpg|thumb|DN class iceboats at the start of a race in [[Znin]], [[Poland]]]]\n[[File:JWC-JEC 2019 IceOptimists.jpg|thumb|IceOptimists]]\n[[File:SIK-N157 14.jpg|thumb|Monotype XV]]\n\n=== International DN ===\nThe [[International DN]] class is the most popular class in both North America and Europe. It is a one-person wood boat twelve feet long with a cross-plank eight feet long that carries a mast {{convert|16|ft|m}} high. Modern competitive DNs use flexible masts commonly made of composite materials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227121944/https://ice.idniyra.org/|title=IDNIYRA {{!}} International DN Ice Yacht Racing Association|date=2017-12-27|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The DN 60 derives its name from the 1937 request of ''The Detroit News'' for a high-performance, inexpensive, home-built iceboat design. Modern DNs share many one-design features with the original boat, including the basic aerodynamic fuselage design, runner configurations and {{convert|60|sqft|m2}} of high-performance sail.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Staff|first=|date=January 1982|title=Endless winter, the iceboater's dream|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mgMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA59&dq=skeeter+ice+boat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjB0fvbnOnoAhWohHIEHQrjBWUQ6AEwAnoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=skeeter%20ice%20boat&f=false|journal=Changing Times-The Kiplinger Magazine|volume=36|issue=1|pages=58-9|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== IceOptimist ===\nThe IceOptimist is a youth iceboat class that uses the sails and the rig of the [[Optimist (dinghy)|International Optimist dinghy]]. The first design was built in [[Estonia]] in 1978, with scaled-down elements of a [[International DN|DN]]. In [[2002]], the class was registered under the guardianship of IDNIYRA Europe with the permission of IODA. World and European Championships are sailed each winter with a fleet of approximately 40 racers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idniyra.eu/juniors/|title=ICE OPTI and DN JUNIOR \u2013 IDNIYRA \u2013 Europe|website=idniyra.eu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Monotype XV ===\nThe Monotype XV is a class of iceboat based on a 1932 design by Estonian, Erik von Holst. It may be single or double-handed. The [[One-Design|one-design]] class is built according to close specifications, little changed since the 1930s. It is the largest one-design iceboat class in Europe and the only double-handed iceboat class for which there are international championships. The {{Convert|205|kg|lb|abbr=|adj=on}} is {{Convert|7.5*4.2|m|ft|abbr=}} in length and width with a {{Convert|7.2|m|ft|abbr=|adj=on}} high mast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iceboat.org/2019/03/04/monotype-xv-european-championship/|title=Monotype XV European Championship|last=Whitehorse|first=Deb|date=2019-03-04|website=iceboat.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Skeeter ===\nThe Skeeter class is divided into sub-classes (A, B and C) all of which are limited to {{convert|75|sqft|m2}} of sail area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iceboat.org/regattas/internationalskeeterassociation/|title=International Skeeter Association|website=iceboat.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> ''A-class'' boats may be single or two-place tandem with a mast that does not exceed {{Convert|28.5|ft|m|abbr=}}. They may incorporate carbon fiber construction.<ref name=\":3\" /> ''B-class'' boats have seats for two (side by side). ''C-class'' skeeters may be single or two-place tandem with a mast that does not exceed {{Convert|20.25|ft|m|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://139655-585885-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/ISARules.pdf|title=General rules and regulations of the International Skeeter Association|last=Class committee|first=|date=October 16, 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Sail boat]]\n* [[Sailing]]\n* [[Land sailing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PE8mCZOmrEo Video overview of DN iceboating]\n* {{Commons category-inline|Iceboats}}\n\n{{Application of wind energy}}\n{{Ice}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ice Boat}}\n[[Category:Ice yachting]]\n[[Category:Sailboat types]]\n[[Category:Racing vehicles]]\n[[Category:Human-powered watercraft]]\n\n[[de:Eissegeln]]\n", "name_user": "HopsonRoad", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSpeed:10 => 5 + refs.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iceboat"}
{"title_page": "Nekkerspoel", "text_new": "'''Nekkerspoel''' is a hamlet of [[Mechelen]], [[Belgium]], immediately east of the city. The name means pool of one or more ''Nekker''s or water demons (in older Flemish ''necker'', devil, evil spirit; from [[Latin]] ''niger'', <span style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">''negr-'',</span> black),<span style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"><ref>{{in lang|nl}} [http://www.volksverhalenbank.be/zoeken/zoeken_Detail.cfm?ID=11635 folk story ''Nekker startles couple''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928100901/http://www.volksverhalenbank.be/zoeken/zoeken_Detail.cfm?ID=11635 |date=2007-09-28 }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n|editor=[[C.P. Serrure]]\n|title=Vaderlandsch museum voor Nederduitsche letterkunde, oudheid en geschiedenis, volume 5\n|url=http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/_vad004vade05_01/index.htm\n|chapter=15th century ''Jaerboeken der Thieltsche Rhetorijkkamer''\n|chapterurl=http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/_vad004vade05_01/_vad004vade05_01_0003.htm\n|quote=''Necker'' is een oud Vlaemsch woord, hetwelk beteekent ''duivel'' of ''booze geest''\n|publisher=H. Hoste\n|location=Ghent\n|language=Dutch\n|date=1865\n|pages=42\n|isbn= |oclc= |doi= |id= \n|accessdate=2007-01-27}} (\"''Necker'' is an old-Flemish word that means ''devil'' or ''evil spirit''\") footnote in 1865. On [http://www.dbnl.org dbnl] website</ref></span> and it is assumed that in earlier centuries locals taking a shortcut trodding through the marshlands of which the Mechels Broek still remains, may have strayed off safer pathways and lost their lives. In 1904, remnants dating from the [[La T\u00e8ne]] era of a settlement of several wooden houses and an 8.4 metre long canoe cut out of an oak tree-trunk, were found at a depth of 5 metres.<span style=\"vertical-align:middle\"><ref>\n{{cite web\n |title       = Virtueel museum: De metaaltijden\n |publisher   = archeoweb Mechelen\n |url         = http://archeoweb.mechelen.be/NL/virtueel/tijdslijn-detail.asp?id=2\n |accessdate  = January 27, 2007\n |language    = nl\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070430185513/http://archeoweb.mechelen.be/NL/virtueel/tijdslijn-detail.asp?id=2\n |archivedate = April 30, 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nThis hamlet was already well-populated and built-up at a time that otherwise mainly a few monasteries were seen outside the city's former walls. Meanwhile, it obtained Mechelen's secondary station on Belgium's major Brussels-Mechelen-Antwerp railway, and the [[Mechelen Toy Museum|Toy Museum]] (''Speelgoedmuseum'') with exhibits covering 7,000 m\u00b2 in the former furniture manufacturer's Nova building.\n[[Image:NMBS 838 MS75 in Mechelen Nekkerspoel.jpg|thumb|400px|center|Station Mechelen Nekkerspoel, train 838 (type MS75) arriving at platform 4, direction Brussels]]\nBy the end of the third quarter of the 20th century, sand from nearby rivers had been disposed on a part of the Mechels Broek along the river [[Dijle]]. Shortly thereafter sandwinning created two large pools while the remainder physically supports the provincial sports and recreation complex De Nekker, which in summer also offers swimming at the artificial beach in a safe-guarded part of the larger of the man-made pools.<span style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"><ref>Note: 'De Nekker' is to the east of Mechelen at Nekkerspoel. The consumers magazine Test Aankoop (by De Verbruikersunie Test-Aankoop vzw) had mistakenly by that name described 'Battenbroek' at the Mechlinian hamlet of Walem in an article about swimming waters in Belgium, but rectified it in a later number; the actual 'De Nekker' was never described. As only the larger pool has been used for swimming at De Nekker whereas at Battenbroek the larger one is used for waterskiing and the smaller one was unofficially though intensively used for swimming, in view of [http://ec.europa.eu/water/water-bathing/report2006/be_lists_maps.pdf this water-bathing report] mentioning a large and a small pool and their location north of Mechelen on a map, this confounding may originate or also occur on that [[European Commission]] page.</ref></span> Though from beside its main building one may start walking along the Mechels Broek, the latter's visitor centre is at the [[Mechelen|Mechlinian]] suburb of Muizen and the nature reserve stretches onto the neighbouring municipality of [[Bonheiden]].\n\nLocated between the actual hamlet and the sports complex, the 18,000 m\u00b2 multi-functional events hall named Nekkerhal is widely known for e.g. [[erotica]] exhibitions (''Mega Erotica Beurs'')<span style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"><ref>\n{{cite web\n |title       = Mega Erotica Beurs\n |publisher   = Nekkerhal vzw\n |url         = http://www.nekkerhal.be/toonevenement.php?id=44\n |accessdate  = January 27, 2007\n |language    = nl\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061215222428/http://www.nekkerhal.be/toonevenement.php?id=44\n |archivedate = December 15, 2006\n}}</ref></span> once in a blue moon but each time with broad media coverage,<span style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"><ref>\n{{cite web\n |author      = (kcb)\n |title       = Wervelende shows op Mega Erotica Beurs (''Whirling shows on Mega Erotica Fair'')\n |publisher   = newspaper Het Nieuwsblad/Het Volk\n |date        = January 13, 2007\n |url         = http://www.nieuwsblad.be/Article/Detail.aspx?articleID=g5416td31\n |accessdate  = January 28, 2007\n |language    = nl\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927015218/http://www.nieuwsblad.be/Article/Detail.aspx?articleID=g5416td31\n |archivedate = September 27, 2007\n}}</ref></span> its regular [[flea market]]s (''Bras Vlooienmarkt''), sports promotion days ('''Doe-aan-sportbeurs''), and other temporary events drawing public with a specific interest such as informatics or specialty cars, or of a particular profession as for the International Furniture Festival trade market. It had originally been built by the municipality for housing Europe's largest [[cooperative]] vegetable [[auction]], when this had outgrown its buildings along Mechelen's minor ring road that replaced the city walls. By the time it was finished however, the auction had moved to the neighbouring municipality of [[Sint-Katelijne-Waver]]. Mechelen leaves the property in the care of the Nekkerhal non-profit organization.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Mechelen]]\n* [[Neck (water spirit)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070207032228/http://www.speelgoedmuseum.be/pages/mus_hoofd_EN.htm Toy Museum]\n* [http://www.zuidrand.be/Fotos/MechelsBroek/MechelsBroek.htm Mechels Broek nature reserve] photos on environmental organization ''Natuurpunt vzw'''s website\n* {{in lang|nl}} [http://www.natuurpunt.be/default.asp?ID=1406 Mechels Broek nature reserve] description on environmental organization ''Natuurpunt vzw'''s website\n* [http://www.inenuitmechelen.be/en/vrijetijd/recreatiedomeinen.phtml ''De Nekker'' sports and recreation complex (and a few similar sites at Mechelen)]\n* {{in lang|nl}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070126082141/http://www.provant.be/en/vrije_tijd/domains/de_nekker/index.jsp ''De Nekker'' sports and recreation complex]\n* {{in lang|nl}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20061218192506/http://www.nekkerhal.be/toonevenement.php?id=46 Nekkerhal multi-functional events hall]\n\n{{coord|51|1|51|N|4|29|56|E|type:city_region:BE_source:nlwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Lordship of Mechelen]]\n[[Category:Mechelen]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Antwerp (province)]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Belgium]]\n", "text_old": "'''Nekkerspoel''' is a hamlet of [[Mechelen]], [[Belgium]], immediately east of the city. The name means pool of one or more ''Nekker''s or water demons (in older Flemish ''necker'', devil, evil spirit; from [[Latin]] ''niger'', <span style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">''negr-'',</span> black),<span style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"><ref>{{in lang